{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012qx9HXu54agEcS8zocMsv4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! \n\n- `search-direct` → `es-alpha` has: `.geoip_databases` and `app-logs` (no `app-data`)\n- `search-http` → `es-beta` has 3 `es-alpha` nodes visible (wait, that's `es-alpha-0,1,2` responding)\n\nWait, `search-http` selects `app=es-beta` but shows `es-alpha-0,1,2` nodes... That can't be right.\nLet me reconsider the selectors: `search-http` and `search-alt` both point to `app=es-beta`, while `search-direct` points to `app=es-alpha`. So if `search-http` is returning `es-alpha` nodes, maybe `es-beta-0` is somehow connected to the `es-alpha` cluster? I'm seeing the service definitions now—`search-http` points to `es-beta`, but there's also `search-alt` pointing to `es-beta` and `search-direct` pointing to `es-alpha`. The selector mismatch is becoming clearer, but something still doesn't add up about why `es-beta-0` is reporting `es-alpha` nodes. I see the grep output is showing multiple service definitions separated by `--` delimiters. The `search-http` service has `es-beta` in its selector, then `search-alt` also points to `es-beta`, and finally `search-direct` points to `es-alpha`. So there are actually three different services with two different selector targets across them.\n\nBut here's the key insight: if `/_cat/nodes` returned `es-alpha-0,1,2` nodes, then `es-beta` isn't a separate cluster at all—it's actually part of the same cluster as `es-alpha`. That means `search-http` is routing to the same cluster as `search-direct`, just through a different service. When I queried the `es-beta` service, it returned nodes from the `es-alpha` cluster, which means `es-beta-0` is actually part of the `es-alpha` cluster despite having a different `cluster.name` in its ConfigMap. This shouldn't be possible since Elasticsearch refuses to join clusters with mismatched names, unless the node joine